
       Java Collection Hierarchy
      =========================

                 Iterable
                     |
                 Collection
        ┌────────────┼─────────────┐
       List          Set           Queue
        |             |              |
  ┌─────┼─────┐   ┌───┼────┐   ┌─────┼────────┐
 ArrayList  LinkedList  HashSet  PriorityQueue  Deque
 Vector                 LinkedHashSet          |
  |                         |               ArrayDeque
 Stack                 SortedSet
                           |
                        TreeSet
1️⃣ Iterable (Top Level)

Enables for-each loop

Has iterator() method

for(String s : list) { }
2️⃣ Collection (Root Interface)

Base interface for all collections

Common methods:

add()

remove()

size()

contains()

3️⃣ List (Ordered, Allows Duplicates)

✔ Maintains insertion order
✔ Allows duplicates

Implementations:

ArrayList → Fast access

LinkedList → Fast insert/delete

Vector → Synchronized (legacy)

Stack → LIFO (legacy)

4️⃣ Set (No Duplicates)

✔ Unique elements only

Implementations:

HashSet → No order

LinkedHashSet → Insertion order

TreeSet → Sorted order

5️⃣ Queue (FIFO)

✔ Used for processing tasks

Implementations:

PriorityQueue → Priority-based

Deque (Double-ended queue)

ArrayDeque

6️⃣ Map (❗Not part of Collection)

Stores key–value pairs

              Map
               |
    ┌──────────┼──────────┐
 HashMap   LinkedHashMap  Hashtable
               |
           SortedMap
               |
             TreeMap

Map Key Points

Keys are unique

Values can be duplicate

Hashtable → synchronized (legacy)

One-Line Interview Summary ⭐

Collection is the root interface for List, Set, and Queue, while Map is separate and stores key-value pairs.
